                  <handDesc>
                     
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Irregular, uneven</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red (vivid vermilion).</seg>
                        <date>Late 17th - early 18th century</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>
                              <abbr>፳ኤል</abbr> for <expan>እስራኤል </expan> (ʾƎsrāʾel).</item>
                           <item>
                              <abbr>፳ኤላዊ</abbr> for <expan>እስራኤላዊ (ʾƎsrāʾelawi) is also found
                              </expan> (<locus target="#3va">3va</locus> l.2).</item>
                        </list>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Nomina sacra (only St Mary); name of the donor (fol.
                           103rb); the word salām; incipits of the text and its subsections (a few
                           lines are rubricated, alternating with black lines, in the pages opening
                           the commemorative notices for each month: fols. 3r, 51v, 105r); elements
                           of punctuation signs; elements of Ethiopic numerals.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The handwriting appears irregular and
                        uneven, mostly due to irregular ruling (c.p. <locus target="#6v">6v</locus>,
                        7r), different size of columns (c.p. <locus target="#5r">5r</locus>, 6v, 7r,
                        98r), different size of the letters (c.p. <locus target="#51rc">51rc</locus>).
                        </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic"> The scribe tends to small, broad,
                        rounded, broadly spaced
                        letters.</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic"> Loops of the vowel markers tend to be
                        open.</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic"> Particular features are:
                        </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h6" script="Ethiopic"> - the form of 'one' (፩) is rounded at
                        the bottom and upwards-oriented (e.g.: <locus target="#5vb">5vb</locus>
                        l.1).</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h7" script="Ethiopic"> - the horizontal strokes containing
                        the numbers are constituted by dots (eg. <locus target="#97vc">97vc</locus>
                        l.2, 107ra l.19), or by the combination of dots and stroke (eg. <locus target="#4va">4va</locus> l.10, 100va l.1)
                        </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h8" script="Ethiopic"> - the letter ሐ often has an unusually
                        long hairline stroke at the top (eg. <locus target="#7rb">7rb</locus> l.19,
                        10va
                        l.12)</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h9" script="Ethiopic"> - the loops of ቶ and ቆ are placed on
                        the left side of the horizontal stroke, not in the
                        middle,</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h10" script="Ethiopic"> mostly connected to the left stroke
                        instead of being connected the upper horizontal stroke (eg. for ቶ: <locus target="#6rb">6rb</locus> l.4, 7va l.11, 9va l.1; eg. for ቆ: <locus target="#4rb">4rb</locus> l.1, 4rc
                        l.1).</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h11" script="Ethiopic"> - the word ʾƎgziʾabǝḥer is in the
                        most cases written with a
                        ligature.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
